00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:22.740
&gt;&gt; Good evening, ladies
and gentleman.

00:00:22.740 --> 00:00:24.400
Bienvenidos.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:27.590
Welcome to the Pickford,
the very intimate,

00:00:27.590 --> 00:00:29.400
lovely, beautiful Pickford.

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.160
We're very glad to have you here.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:33.530
I am Marie Arana.

00:00:33.530 --> 00:00:36.140
And I am here to welcome
you on behalf

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:38.840
of the Librarian Hispanic
Initiative.

00:00:38.840 --> 00:00:44.390
This is an initiative that was
begun by the Librarian of Congress,

00:00:44.390 --> 00:00:49.510
James Billington, who
just about a year ago.

00:00:49.510 --> 00:00:54.060
[ Applause ]

00:00:54.060 --> 00:00:57.690
Just about a year ago,
Dr. Billington decided

00:00:57.690 --> 00:01:02.760
that an organization was
needed, an initiative was needed

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:08.690 position:56%
with a working group behind it to
better serve the Hispanic population

00:01:08.690 --> 00:01:15.130
of this country and to better
represent the collection,

00:01:15.130 --> 00:01:21.200 position:56%
the Luso-Hispanic collection in this
institution, which is the largest

00:01:21.200 --> 00:01:26.090
and finest Hispanic
collection in the world.

00:01:26.090 --> 00:01:30.510
And to bring attention to that,
not only for the Hispanic-Americans

00:01:30.510 --> 00:01:36.520
of this country, but for all of the
world and all the Americas, really.

00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:39.460
And the third part of
this initiative was

00:01:39.460 --> 00:01:43.690
to better represent the Hispanic
population within the institution

00:01:43.690 --> 00:01:45.200
of the Library of Congress.

00:01:45.200 --> 00:01:51.520
So this has been a very busy year
for the Hispanic Working Group.

00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:53.720
And I think a very productive year.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:57.780
And this is really a
product of their efforts.

00:01:57.780 --> 00:02:02.480
I want to say a little
bit about the program.

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:10.780
You know, a vibrant American
theatre, which celebrates and stars

00:02:10.780 --> 00:02:15.080 position:56%
and serves Hispanics, has been
flourishing in this country probably

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:17.040
since the mid-19th Century.

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:19.370
And that's more than 150 hears.

00:02:19.370 --> 00:02:26.010
But in fact, very few contemporary
American historians have written

00:02:26.010 --> 00:02:29.900
about it or know about
or have recorded it.

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:34.830
Certainly, little of that story has
been recorded in any of the annals

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:37.620
of American theatre history even.

00:02:37.620 --> 00:02:42.670 position:56%
And now come these two scholar, Tony
Mata [phonetic] and Ralf Remshardt

00:02:42.670 --> 00:02:47.380
to correct that oversight and
to rescue a really vivid slice

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:51.580
of history, the history of New
York's dynamic Latino Theatre

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:54.010
over the course of
the past 50 years.

00:02:54.010 --> 00:02:57.400
They call it the Theatre
of Rice and Beans.

00:02:57.400 --> 00:02:59.030
The documentary you're about to see

00:02:59.030 --> 00:03:03.280
and hear represents a major
corrective and one that we want

00:03:03.280 --> 00:03:05.530
to honor here at the
Library of Congress.

00:03:05.530 --> 00:03:09.350
We hope that you appreciate
its broader cultural context,

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:14.120
the sweeping infusion of the
Hispanic arts that Professor Mata's

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:18.540
and Professor Remshardt
very moving film represents,

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:23.890
especially as they engage in
conversation with two giants

00:03:23.890 --> 00:03:28.030
of the Washington D.C.'s
storied GALA Theatre here

00:03:28.030 --> 00:03:29.870
in D.C. [foreign language].

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:34.600
We're very fortunate
to have these very.

00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:39.040
[ Applause ]

00:03:39.040 --> 00:03:42.710
Very fortunate to have these very
engaged witnesses join us tonight

00:03:42.710 --> 00:03:45.090
in a tribute to the wider story.

